WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.420
I'm actually going to talk about clonal hematopoiesis in breast cancer survivors treated with metformin

00:00:05.420 --> 00:00:10.460
as an allegory for how we might think about interventional clinical trials in clonal hematopoiesis.

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:13.640
These are my disclosures.

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:16.680
And before I talk about the specific project, I want to give you a little bit of background

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.260
about clonal hematopoiesis in cancer generally.

00:00:19.260 --> 00:00:24.440
We understand that the rate of clonal hematopoiesis in cancer survivors is actually quite high.

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:27.880
It is in about a third of individuals who are over the age of 65.

00:00:27.880 --> 00:00:32.640
I'll remind you that corresponds to a VAF of about 2% or greater in the size of these

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:33.680
clones.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:38.200
On average, you could think of it as being 20 years accelerated compared to a non-cancer

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:39.200
population.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:43.720
And we know that clonal hematopoiesis in this cancer survivor population has adverse outcomes,

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:49.840
not just from the increased rates of therapy-related myeloid malignancies that we see, but outcomes

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:52.220
that relate to overall survival more generally.

00:00:52.220 --> 00:00:56.960
And that's true not only in lymphoma cases with heavy chemotherapy exposure, but in cancers

00:00:56.960 --> 00:00:57.860
generally across the board.

00:00:57.860 --> 00:01:03.980
So, there are some differences in the pattern of clonal hematopoiesis that we see in cancer

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:05.460
survivors as well.

00:01:05.460 --> 00:01:09.640
We know that there isn't just a higher rate of overall mutations in this population, but

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:12.920
there is a particular difference in the type of mutations that we see.

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:20.040
We see more mutations in DNA damage response genes like TP53, PPM1D, CHK2, and ATM.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:24.420
And while age is still the predominant risk factor, and DNMT3A is still by far the most

00:01:24.420 --> 00:01:27.840
common mutation, we see that several of these DNA damage responses are more common.

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:28.840
And we see that the number of mutations in the DNA damage response genes are actually

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:34.080
increased in response to this selective pressure of cytotoxic chemotherapy or radiation over

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:39.960
time, whereas the more traditional chip genes, DNMT3A, TET2, and ASXL1, are less expanded

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:44.460
by these interventions, even if they are more prevalent in this patient population.

00:01:44.460 --> 00:01:49.940
So with DNMT3A being the most common mutation, there's a lot of interest in designing clinical

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:53.840
trials that might be able to target clonal hematopoiesis in this context to mitigate

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:57.640
some of the adverse effects that we see in cardiovascular disease and other disease types.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.820
And I'll show you why this could be quite difficult.

00:02:00.820 --> 00:02:05.960
There is some real recent interest in doing this for a particular type of DNMT3A mutation,

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:11.180
the R882 mutation, which is actually considered more adverse as it's enriched in AML over

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:15.280
MDS and in MDS over the general population.

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:18.680
And these three articles that were published recently suggest that this particular clone

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.560
in DNMT3A is maintained by mitochondrial metabolism.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:26.620
And that targeting mitochondrial membrane potential may be a therapeutic modality to

00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:27.820
decrease the fitness of this clone.

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:32.120
And that we might be able to do this with a common drug like metformin that not only

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:37.380
lowers glucose levels, but targets cytochrome oxidase and inhibits this membrane mitochondrial

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:39.180
membrane potential.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:43.760
So the evidence that supported this was noting that when you take mouse cells with an equivalent

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:48.680
mutation in DNMT3A, that they have more colony formation in vitro, and you can mitigate this

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:51.080
by adding metformin to the mix.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:54.900
You can actually do this in vivo in transgenic transplant models, where you can see greater

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:57.800
engraftment with the mutant clone present.

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:04.720
And you can even mimic this in human cells, that have had DNMT3A knocked down with a short

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:09.800
hairpin, showing enhanced colony formation that again is mitigated by the addition of

00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:10.800
metformin.

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.720
So it looks like a hopeful strategy for trying to remove the selective advantage these mutant

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:15.720
cells might have.

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:21.000
And in a very, I think, really elegant population study, and George Vassilou and his team looked

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.160
at patients or individuals who had been sequenced for clonal metopoiesis genes, but who had received

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:27.780
metformin with several curatives.

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:29.780
So you can see that this is a very important study.

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:30.780
And then you can see that this is a very important study.

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:31.780
And you can see that this is a very important study.

